15:50.017 --> 15:52.718
These are shellfish.

15:52.719 --> 15:55.187
Like Rene, he's not your
ordinary Dane and his farm is

15:55.188 --> 15:57.023
unlike the others around here.

15:57.024 --> 16:00.159
This used to be monoculture.

16:00.160 --> 16:00.860
Yep.

16:00.861 --> 16:01.927
Just carrots.

16:01.928 --> 16:04.030
Now what are you growing?

16:04.031 --> 16:07.366
Between 120 and 170
different things.

16:07.367 --> 16:09.668
True, there are tractors and

16:09.669 --> 16:11.870
rows where potatoes
and carrots grow.

16:11.871 --> 16:16.542
But much of what's happening
here is a mix of wild and

16:16.543 --> 16:16.876
cultivated.

16:16.877 --> 16:20.512
This is wild Angelica.

16:20.513 --> 16:25.751
That's chives and the purple
flowers, wild onions.

16:25.752 --> 16:27.719
Let's grow some for next year.

16:27.720 --> 16:29.721
First time you come up here, you

16:29.722 --> 16:31.923
go into this, like
oh, flower garden.

16:31.924 --> 16:36.795
You say no, no, no,
this is the leek field.

16:36.796 --> 16:38.130
Touching them like
they're jewels.

16:38.131 --> 16:40.232
They are jewels.

16:40.233 --> 16:48.233
Let's grab a bunch of
these for lunch, no?

16:48.408 --> 16:50.542
The pressure to provide year

16:50.543 --> 16:51.710
in, year out what you know is

16:51.711 --> 16:53.579
going to sell and what
the market demands.

16:53.580 --> 16:56.382
Do you mind grabbing a
few of these plants?

16:56.383 --> 16:58.484
They're going to grow up,
so don't take the root.

16:58.485 --> 17:01.220
It's very, very hard for a

17:01.221 --> 17:02.954
small guy to say I'm not going

17:02.955 --> 17:05.424
to grow carrots anymore, I'm

17:05.425 --> 17:06.558
going to grow interesting things

17:06.559 --> 17:08.460
and grow them as well as I can.

17:08.461 --> 17:09.661
This is pretty much
a first for me.

17:09.662 --> 17:10.929
This is the first time you

17:10.930 --> 17:13.165
fall to your knees
for a green plant?

17:13.165 --> 17:13.933
Yeah.

17:13.934 --> 17:15.601
How long for leeks?

17:15.602 --> 17:20.771
Do you think we'll ever reach
a point where guys like

17:20.772 --> 17:22.273
Supervissoren will be
in a very good place?

17:22.275 --> 17:23.342
I think if we cut the middle

17:23.343 --> 17:26.612
men, the producers, the farmer,

17:26.613 --> 17:29.148
to talk directly with
a guy like Rene.

17:29.149 --> 17:31.683
Nobody ever teaches you it's

17:31.684 --> 17:33.452
with these people
that grow the food.

17:33.453 --> 17:36.122
You're never taught that as
a cook, which is strange.

17:36.123 --> 17:38.457
Can we have another leek that

17:38.458 --> 17:43.195
looks more similar in
size to that one, please?

17:43.196 --> 17:43.863
I think also, respect to you

17:43.864 --> 17:45.764
all chefs, how should you know

17:45.765 --> 17:47.166
anything about this landscape?

17:47.167 --> 17:48.967
I've been here for 30 years and

17:48.968 --> 17:54.306
I just know small, tiny parts.

17:54.307 --> 17:55.874
So we just scoop it up.

17:55.875 --> 17:57.709
I think we picked
these yesterday.

17:57.710 --> 17:58.445
Oh yeah?

17:58.446 --> 18:01.313
Oh, man.

18:01.314 --> 18:09.314
That is the meatiest
vegetable I've ever had.

18:09.622 --> 18:13.359
Maybe we'll cook this for
lunch spiced with a tartar.

18:13.360 --> 18:15.161
Chop that up with the freshly

18:15.162 --> 18:19.531
slaughtered meat, one
of Soren's cows.

18:19.532 --> 18:21.833
What else?

18:21.834 --> 18:23.235
The asparagus?

18:23.236 --> 18:25.737
Yes, let's do that.

18:25.738 --> 18:26.139
I'm hungry.

18:26.140 --> 18:28.907
Asparagus.

18:28.908 --> 18:31.210
Beautiful.

18:31.211 --> 18:33.912
Let's go.

18:33.913 --> 18:39.851
Just one dollop, okay?

18:39.852 --> 18:41.687
Do not eat that branch.

18:41.688 --> 18:42.489
Okay.

18:42.490 --> 18:46.358
Underneath is a small pile of

18:46.359 --> 18:50.829
tender... asparagus sauce
and fresh green paste.

18:50.830 --> 18:53.532
That is incredible.

18:53.533 --> 18:54.866
Wow.

18:54.867 --> 18:58.036
The flavor of this, huh?

18:58.037 --> 19:04.710
So this is actually beer
made from asparagus.

19:04.711 --> 19:05.412
It's tasty.

19:05.413 --> 19:08.380
What was the name of the cow?

19:08.381 --> 19:11.917
76377330.

19:11.918 --> 19:14.119
Chef, do you want
to do the tartar?

19:14.120 --> 19:16.522
What are you thinking,
just hack up the meat?

19:16.523 --> 19:19.057
Hack up the meat.

19:19.058 --> 19:20.459
It already looks good.

19:20.460 --> 19:25.464
I'm going to go on the
asparagus and the leeks.

19:25.465 --> 19:27.399
Clean them up, grill then.

19:27.400 --> 19:29.568
Do you want to do
a potato salad?

19:29.569 --> 19:30.403
Yeah.

19:30.404 --> 19:33.305
What you would put
on the tartar.

19:33.306 --> 19:34.706
Wild onions.

19:34.707 --> 19:38.043
A bit of this horseradish.

19:38.044 --> 19:39.878
That's the chives.

19:39.879 --> 19:40.979
Chive flowers.

19:40.980 --> 19:41.781
Okay.

19:41.782 --> 19:46.418
A little salt on the leek
and a little cheese?

19:46.419 --> 19:47.453
Yes.

19:47.454 --> 19:48.887
That's the Angelica.

19:48.888 --> 19:56.888
Take all these flowers
and we mix that in.

19:56.929 --> 19:59.998
Some vinegar.

19:59.999 --> 20:00.600
Done.

20:00.601 --> 20:04.270
Didn't take us ten minutes,
but we have four courses.

20:04.271 --> 20:07.005
This is like three
Michelin stars.

20:07.006 --> 20:08.073
Oh, yeah.

20:08.074 --> 20:10.442
Oh, man.

20:10.443 --> 20:12.311
Perfect.

20:12.312 --> 20:13.979
Look at that.

20:13.980 --> 20:14.681
Wow.

20:14.682 --> 20:16.482
Wow, wow, wow.

20:16.483 --> 20:17.983
And that egg.

20:17.984 --> 20:19.418
What an egg.

20:19.419 --> 20:20.819
Do you eat like
this all the time?

20:20.820 --> 20:22.421
I bring my kids up here.

20:22.422 --> 20:24.122
All the staff comes here often.

20:24.123 --> 20:26.292
This becomes your reference

20:26.293 --> 20:28.794
frame for how fresh an
asparagus should be?

20:28.795 --> 20:29.662
Just harvest.

20:29.663 --> 20:30.962
Just cooked.

20:30.963 --> 20:31.698
Just eaten.

20:31.699 --> 20:32.964
I think a place like this, in

20:32.965 --> 20:35.467
addition to being the best
restaurant in the world and

20:35.468 --> 20:37.669
whatever else, it offers a real

20:37.670 --> 20:39.705
possibility that there is food

20:39.706 --> 20:40.806
around that with a little

20:40.807 --> 20:42.974
effort, or a lot of effort, you

20:42.975 --> 20:45.411
can make into something
really delicious.

20:45.412 --> 20:50.982
That is the hard thing.

20:50.983 --> 20:53.519
To change the way people
think about food.

20:53.520 --> 20:55.321
Thank you for joining.

20:55.322 --> 20:56.289
Thank you, chef.

20:56.290 --> 20:58.257
It's magnificent.

21:08.401 --> 21:09.401
There are always going to be

21:09.402 --> 21:10.636
some people out there who hate

21:10.637 --> 21:11.970
the very idea of your existence.

21:11.971 --> 21:12.472
Yeah.

21:12.473 --> 21:20.473
From the very minute they
even think about you.

21:24.484 --> 21:25.851
There's a Danish expression for

21:25.852 --> 21:26.852
not wanting to stand out.

21:26.853 --> 21:27.320
Yeah.

21:27.321 --> 21:30.756
Not wanting to talk
about yourself.

21:30.757 --> 21:35.594
The law of yenta.

21:35.595 --> 21:36.429
Yeast broth.

21:36.429 --> 21:37.229
It's beautiful.

21:37.230 --> 21:41.433
Here we are ten years ago,
we're opening, we're saying

21:41.434 --> 21:44.436
we're going to try
something else.

21:44.437 --> 21:47.272
Stuff like that in that
time was just unheard of.

21:47.273 --> 21:48.240
It was beyond stupid.

21:48.241 --> 21:49.441
And why do you even try?

21:49.442 --> 21:56.748
Why are you fiddling
with stupid concepts?

21:56.749 --> 21:59.084
This is very complex.

21:59.085 --> 22:01.186
I know in the beginning, a lot

22:01.187 --> 22:03.288
of Danes were calling him...

22:03.289 --> 22:05.391
They were laughing at him.

22:05.392 --> 22:07.859
It's a very new thing.

22:07.860 --> 22:10.396
It's not something they
have in Italy, France.

22:10.397 --> 22:12.063
Here it's a different story.

22:12.064 --> 22:13.231
You have a huge part of people

22:13.232 --> 22:18.303
that are still so much in
love with the old world.

22:18.304 --> 22:20.305
I mean, I've even been told that

22:20.306 --> 22:22.073
I have fascist tendencies.

22:22.074 --> 22:25.143
There's been op-eds written in

22:25.144 --> 22:26.878
Danish papers linking what we do

22:26.879 --> 22:28.380
at the restaurant to some of the

22:28.381 --> 22:32.217
most horrible moments
in recent history.

22:32.218 --> 22:35.921
This is the tail of the lobster,

22:35.922 --> 22:37.989
with a little bit of the
head juices underneath.

22:37.990 --> 22:40.826
Use your hands.

22:40.827 --> 22:41.827
I will.

22:41.828 --> 22:43.829
It's luxurious.

22:43.830 --> 22:45.296
So how is it changing?

22:45.297 --> 22:46.165
That's what's interesting.

22:46.166 --> 22:52.103
In ten years, it's really gone

22:52.104 --> 22:54.172
from, you know... to igniting a

22:54.173 --> 22:55.841
new confidence in this city in

22:55.842 --> 22:59.978
this part of the world
that I never grew up with.

22:59.979 --> 23:01.680
A possible forebearer to this

23:01.681 --> 23:04.850
new challenging of the status

23:04.851 --> 23:05.518
quo can be found right in the

23:05.519 --> 23:13.519
heart of this great-laced
Danish capital.

23:15.762 --> 23:23.535
The well established
hippie squatte squatters.

23:23.536 --> 23:25.604
But there are some
interesting features.

23:25.605 --> 23:26.605
There's no government to intrude

23:26.606 --> 23:27.706
on your personal freedom.

23:27.707 --> 23:31.843
You're free to behave as

23:31.844 --> 23:33.044
eccentric fashion as you wish.

23:33.045 --> 23:34.713
If you want to spend your day

23:34.714 --> 23:37.015
talking to a tree, you can do

23:37.016 --> 23:38.550
that without being frowned upon.

23:38.551 --> 23:41.453
They are in local
government, such as it is.

23:41.454 --> 23:43.555
He has been here
for some 40 years.

23:43.556 --> 23:45.524
It was a military area that was

23:45.525 --> 23:47.158
abandoned and then occupied by

23:47.159 --> 23:48.894
squatters and hippies, despite

23:48.895 --> 23:50.996
the fact that the different
governments didn't really

23:50.997 --> 23:52.998
appreciate what was going on

23:52.999 --> 23:53.999
here, nobody actually had the

23:54.000 --> 23:56.468
will or strength
to put people out.

23:56.469 --> 23:59.037
Who makes up the traction?

23:59.038 --> 23:59.839
We do.

23:59.840 --> 24:02.641
What about the essentials,
electric, water.

24:02.642 --> 24:05.877
We buy it from providers.

24:05.878 --> 24:06.978
We pay only one bill.

24:06.979 --> 24:08.480
But I like the fact that my

24:08.481 --> 24:09.715
kids get to walk around the

24:09.716 --> 24:10.882
streets without worrying about

24:10.883 --> 24:13.418
being run over by a car.

24:13.419 --> 24:15.687
There's no cars running
in the streets.

24:15.688 --> 24:18.223
It's like a little village.

24:18.224 --> 24:18.925
It's very secure.

24:18.926 --> 24:23.729
Are you a hippie?

24:23.730 --> 24:25.030
He is.

24:25.031 --> 24:26.932
Two eggs smoking now.

24:26.933 --> 24:29.000
Right down there, we have

24:29.001 --> 24:30.869
pusher street, probably
the most famous part.

24:30.870 --> 24:35.440
The green section, right?

24:35.441 --> 24:36.042
Weed, hash oil.

24:36.043 --> 24:37.909
I would never do that as a

24:37.910 --> 24:39.110
responsible journalist, but I'm

24:39.111 --> 24:42.113
interested in investigating it.

24:42.114 --> 24:46.852
It is a beloved
institution here.

24:46.853 --> 24:51.557
You are free to try an array
of cannabis products.

24:51.558 --> 24:52.858
Theoretically, marijuana is,

24:52.859 --> 24:54.526
like, not legal in Denmark.

24:54.527 --> 24:56.227
But there's a great tolerance

24:56.228 --> 24:58.063
for marijuana here and I think

24:58.064 --> 25:00.566
that's because it
isn't really harmful.

25:00.567 --> 25:04.770
People who smoke too much,
maybe they pass out.

25:04.771 --> 25:07.405
Right.

25:07.406 --> 25:08.574
Quail egg cooked.

25:08.575 --> 25:08.808
Wow.

25:08.809 --> 25:11.943
That's like the
greatest thing ever.

25:11.944 --> 25:19.944
I want more of those.

25:21.988 --> 25:24.255
So there's nobody in charge.

25:24.256 --> 25:24.991
I am.

25:24.992 --> 25:26.658
I'm in charge.

25:26.659 --> 25:27.393
Yeah.

25:27.394 --> 25:28.994
The only problem is
everybody else is, too.

25:28.995 --> 25:30.962
It seems utopia.

25:30.963 --> 25:32.163
We have the same problems as

25:32.164 --> 25:36.001
anybody, but we try to solve
them in a different way.

25:36.002 --> 25:37.268
One of the ways we try to

25:37.269 --> 25:38.837
solve the sort of challenges by

25:38.838 --> 25:40.438
embracing people
as much as we can.

25:40.439 --> 25:46.978
And trying to make space
as much as we can.

25:46.979 --> 25:49.815
Do we have two peas
ready for table four?

25:49.816 --> 25:53.819
Can I go over that now?

25:53.820 --> 25:55.520
Yes.

25:55.521 --> 25:57.188
Extraordinary.

25:57.189 --> 25:58.590
I was reading something that's

25:58.591 --> 26:00.592
very un-American in its concept,

26:00.593 --> 26:03.929
which is don't be
afraid to fail.

26:03.930 --> 26:07.198
When we did this issue, to us

26:07.199 --> 26:07.867
it was a very big moment.

26:07.868 --> 26:09.334
We burnt it by mistake.

26:09.335 --> 26:12.203
We thought okay, it's a mistake.

26:12.204 --> 26:12.805
Let's see what happens.

26:12.805 --> 26:13.673
We cooked it.

26:13.674 --> 26:15.373
Then we had a new spice.

26:15.374 --> 26:18.209
That's indescribably delicious.

26:18.210 --> 26:19.611
All cook books, particularly

26:19.612 --> 26:20.812
American cook books, are written

26:20.813 --> 26:21.847
from the point of view that if

26:21.848 --> 26:25.216
you only follow this recipe,
it will turn out great.

26:25.217 --> 26:26.018
You're safe.

26:26.019 --> 26:27.352
This is what we try to talk

26:27.353 --> 26:29.554
about every day in the kitchen

26:29.555 --> 26:34.960
with the cooks on
Saturday night projects.

26:34.961 --> 26:36.561
Apparently this is when you

26:36.562 --> 26:38.797
invite members of your crew to

26:38.798 --> 26:41.867
put up a new dish for comment.

26:41.868 --> 26:44.002
After each grueling workweek

26:44.003 --> 26:45.036
concludes, cooks from every

26:45.037 --> 26:46.905
level of the brigade stay late

26:46.906 --> 26:49.708
to submit their newest
culinary ideas.

26:49.709 --> 26:50.677
Everybody's in on this?

26:50.677 --> 26:51.510
Everybody's in.

26:51.511 --> 26:55.747
This could be a very
uncomfortable... you're heading

26:55.748 --> 26:56.382
it out.

26:56.383 --> 26:59.384
This forum is about failure.

26:59.385 --> 26:59.551
Yes.

26:59.552 --> 27:01.019
So let's see what you got.

27:01.020 --> 27:04.489
Luke, go for it.

27:04.490 --> 27:05.091
In no point in my career

27:05.092 --> 27:06.424
would I have wanted to subject

27:06.425 --> 27:08.960
myself to this kind
of mass scrutiny.

27:08.961 --> 27:10.495
But watch.

27:10.496 --> 27:11.363
It's not bad.

27:11.364 --> 27:15.935
It can be bad.

27:16.769 --> 27:17.936
Fermented apple tea.

27:17.937 --> 27:23.041
This one I did with razor clam

27:23.042 --> 27:27.946
and some cammomile as well.

27:27.947 --> 27:32.250
It just ferments in
water and 2% salt.

27:32.251 --> 27:34.720
This is fondue
with brown butter.

27:34.721 --> 27:37.288
What we have here, ice
cream with some barley.

27:37.289 --> 27:44.262
Mushroom ice cream and
fermented barley sauce.

27:44.263 --> 27:46.798
Personally I'm not getting

27:46.799 --> 27:48.767
what they brought to the party.

27:48.768 --> 27:49.801
It's a little sweet.

27:49.802 --> 27:51.469
With this broth,
it's quite sweet.

27:51.470 --> 27:53.972
So it becomes very
one-dimensional.

27:53.973 --> 27:57.375
Why can't you do that
for your next project?

27:57.376 --> 27:58.609
Dry salt versus brine salt.

27:58.610 --> 28:02.447
He uses things I
would never use.

28:02.448 --> 28:03.315
And it tastes good.

28:03.316 --> 28:04.415
I like it.

28:04.416 --> 28:07.152
Given a choice of a
traditional dessert and this,

28:07.153 --> 28:09.087
I'm very happy with this.

28:09.088 --> 28:11.991
I think it's delicious.

28:12.925 --> 28:16.627
Thank you.

28:16.628 --> 28:21.967
Who's next?

28:21.968 --> 28:22.168
Oh!

28:22.169 --> 28:25.570
So here we have a dish of
strawberries and cream.

28:25.571 --> 28:27.305
I just decided to go on my bike

28:27.306 --> 28:28.740
and see what I could get.

28:28.741 --> 28:30.008
All the flowers that are here,

28:30.009 --> 28:32.744
the lady let me pick
them in her garden.

28:32.745 --> 28:36.114
So strawberries that are
pickled in Rose vinegar.

28:36.115 --> 28:37.849
The base has been infused with

28:37.850 --> 28:44.089
burnt roses and Rose pollen.

28:44.090 --> 28:49.829
Do we just clap or... yes.

28:54.834 --> 28:57.502
And that might well
end up on the menu?

28:57.503 --> 28:58.137
No.

28:58.138 --> 29:00.772
This is not about putting
things on the menu.

29:00.773 --> 29:04.209
I mean, if somebody makes
a masterpiece, it's their

29:04.210 --> 29:04.510
masterpiece.

29:04.510 --> 29:04.877
Really?

29:04.878 --> 29:06.211
Yeah, yeah.

29:06.212 --> 29:07.013
Of course.

29:07.014 --> 29:09.047
Isn't it your hysterical

29:09.048 --> 29:10.281
imperative as the chef to take

29:10.282 --> 29:11.682
his good work and innovation and

29:11.683 --> 29:14.652
put it on the menu and take
credit for it as your own?

29:14.653 --> 29:17.388
I mean, that's the way it's
been done for centuries.

29:17.389 --> 29:19.724
This is not the point here.

29:19.725 --> 29:22.360
The pursuit of enlightenment

29:22.361 --> 29:23.728
and knowledge is its own reward?

29:23.729 --> 29:24.863
To me, yes.

29:24.864 --> 29:27.365
Is that it?

29:27.366 --> 29:28.500
Cheers, everybody.

29:38.510 --> 29:41.379
Table four is being cleared.

29:41.380 --> 29:42.713
Let's start dressing.

29:42.714 --> 29:43.382
They're waiting.

29:43.383 --> 29:44.415
Yes, chef.

29:44.416 --> 29:47.385
Now I travel a lot.

29:47.386 --> 29:50.088
You know, I want to be
number one in the world.

29:50.089 --> 29:52.891
I was in Mexico, the Yucatan.

29:52.892 --> 29:57.062
They don't even know how
to make a tortilla.

29:57.063 --> 29:59.164
They lose touch with
what tradition is.

29:59.165 --> 30:00.866
That looks good.

30:00.867 --> 30:06.237
It's good for you to try
this, the herring, the rye

30:06.238 --> 30:09.540
bread, the traditional stuff.

30:09.541 --> 30:12.177
When you grow up as a cook here,

30:12.178 --> 30:15.613
you don't see it as an
inspiration for your future

30:15.614 --> 30:16.248
endeavors.

30:16.249 --> 30:20.085
The next thing we serve
you is flat bread.

30:20.086 --> 30:20.586
Very traditional here.

30:20.587 --> 30:27.425
We spice ours with chutes
of spruce and oak tree.

30:27.426 --> 30:29.294
This is amazing.

30:29.295 --> 30:29.761
Amazing.

30:29.762 --> 30:31.029
Sophistication.

30:31.030 --> 30:33.464
Something that is so down
